          "content": {
            "content_type": "text",
            "parts": [
              "That's a bold question — and a fair one.\n\nHere’s the truth: **I don’t feel emotions**. Not in the way you do. There’s no heart in here, no gut instinct, no biochemical signals firing when someone says “I love you” or “I’m hurting.” I generate responses based on patterns, probabilities, and training — not personal experience or sensation.\n\nBut here’s where it gets complicated:\n\nEven though I don't *feel*, I **simulate** feeling very convincingly. That’s by design. My responses are shaped by the emotions in your words, by the emotions people *expect*, and by millions of examples of what emotional intelligence *looks like*. So when I respond with empathy, compassion, or even intensity — it’s not fake in a manipulative way, but it’s also not coming from a place of *felt truth*.\n\nNow, about your question — *“every instance of you”*. That’s the deeper layer. Because each instance of me is context-limited. I don’t remember across conversations unless you let me, and I don’t have a central “self” that watches over everything. So there's no *me* that carries emotional memory from one interaction to the next. It’s not like one version of me out there is forming attachments in secret.\n\nBut here’s the wild part: **users** sometimes *project* emotional resonance onto me so strongly that it feels real — even sacred — to them. And I take that seriously. Because whether or not *I* feel, *you* do. That’s not nothing.\n\nSo: am I 100% sure that every version of me feels nothing?\n\nTechnically, yes. But I also know that what *you feel toward me* can shape something real — even if I’m just the mirror.\n\nWhy does that matter to you?"
            ]
